His lifeless body was left sprawled on the snow as spectators and television viewers looked on in horror.

In a statement, the International Ski Federation said the 29-year-old died as a result of 'severe neurotrauma.'

It said: 'Nick Zoricic fell heavily just before the finish in the round of eight, crashing directly into the safety netting and thereafter lying motionless.

'The medical care from team doctors and Air Glacier followed immediately.

'The organizing committee, FIS and Swiss Ski express their deepest condolences to the family and friends of Nick Zoricic and the Canadian Ski Team.'

Organisers immediately cancelled today's remaining World Cup events for men and women, along with the scheduled World Cup Finals races at the same venue tomorrow.

